Patch Set 2:

This is not working with el8/el9. bpf_lsm use i_security (see bpf_inode()).
So I will switch the test to sb->s_security (only used by smack and selinux):
static inline bool
xfs_create_need_xattr(
        struct inode    *dir,
        struct posix_acl *default_acl,
        struct posix_acl *acl)
{
        if (acl)
                return true;
        if (default_acl)
                return true;
#if IS_ENABLED(CONFIG_SECURITY)
        if (dir->i_sb->s_security)
                return true;
#endif
        return false;
}

(see xfs uptream commit: e6a688c3323840f3e388ba28fd2db86675b79917)

But this will work only with selinux=0 in the kernel cmdline. The new LSM implementation will create s_security after selinux_disable() called:

From /etc/selinux/config
# NOTE: In earlier Fedora kernel builds, SELINUX=disabled would also      
# fully disable SELinux during boot. If you need a system with SELinux    
# fully disabled instead of SELinux running with no policy loaded, you    
# need to pass selinux=0 to the kernel command line. You can use grubby   
# to persistently set the bootloader to boot with selinux=0:           

(see the lsm upstream commit: 1aea7808372eee4ad01f98e064c88c57f1e94855)
